The inscription mentions ‘accounts from Upper Egypt’ in addition to the name of Sekhen/Ka, a Predynastic king who ruled over Upper Egypt just before the first unification of Egypt’s regions into one state. It is the oldest Egyptian inscription in the British Museum.
The correct reading of this king's name is debated. This jar is one of a number of inscriptions on vessels which bear a similar serekh with the 'ka' arms inside. Some are written with the upright 'ka' sign, whilst others bear an upside-down version, interpreted as 'sekhen' ('to embrace').
Published in:
Regulski, I. (ed.), 2022. Hieroglyphs: unlocking ancient Egypt, pp. 168-9; Bibliography:
W. M. F. Petrie, 'Abydos' I (London, 1902), pl. II, 15;
E. A. Wallis Budge 'A Guide to the Fourth, Fifth and Sixth Egyptian Rooms, and the Coptic Room' (London, 1922), 248 (right);
