This bust derives from a colossal statue that represented Ramses II standing, hands crossed over the chest, and holding the insignia of royalty, the flail and the crook. Measuring 22 7/8 inches (58 cm) high, the base of the statue supporting the royal feet was unearthed much later in the temple of the god Khnum at Elephantine and recently identified by the author of this entry as belonging to the bust. The royal costume was certainly a kilt, completed with an animal tail hanging between the legs. The tip of the tail is still preserved on the lower part of this sculpture, which is kept on Elephantine.
